Dear Rajarshi,
 
You (@TheRajarshi) asked me (@homam108) on Twitter: "What is the exact
meaning of the term Kutastha?"
 
I have an answer longer than Twitter allows.

 

In Sanskrita, words have several meanings and subtle concepts are cleverly
expressed with layers of meanings.

 

Stha means "firmly placed/established in".

 

Kuta means a group/collection (e.g. ashta graha kuta). It also means a
dwelling/house. It also means an illusion. It also means the horn of an
animal. It also means the highest point/pinnacle/summit.

 

We beings are made up of a collection of entities such as senses, manas,
chitta, buddhi etc. Kutastha is the intelligence that brings them all
together and stays in the group as what binds them as one thing (i.e. that
which is present in the collection).

 

Every perishable structure (including any being or any world) in this cosmos
is like a temporary dwelling. Kutastha is the dweller of that dwelling (that
which is well-established in the dwelling).

 

Every being in this cosmos is like an illusion, in the sense that the
reality of its existence depends on the frame of reference. Kutastha is its
unborn and perennial essence that exists within, irrespective of the frame
of reference (that which truly exists within the illusion).

 

Kutastha is also the Absolute Essence firmly placed in the sahasrara chakra
(that which is firmly placed in the horn).

 

In the end, when a being reaches the pinnacle of its awareness, the
awareness will point to Self. Kutastha is Self that is rooted in the highest
awareness (that which is rooted in the pinnacle).

 

All these are "exact meanings" at various levels of understanding/awareness.

 
Best regards,
Narasimha
